`scripts/` is the collection of standalone CI/lint checks and doc-generation scripts invoked by ctx-verify and by hand — none of these are library code, each is a self-contained script with its own exit-code contract.

All the lint scripts (`cycle_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, `retired_terms_check.sh`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`) share the same enumeration convention: `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard` rather than a filesystem walk, so results are a pure function of git state and never race a concurrent `target/` writer, and untracked-but-unignored files are checked while `.gitignore`d ones aren't. They also share output format: `FAIL: path:line: message` to stderr, with a trailing `/dev/null` appended to grep invocations to force `path:line:` prefixing even for single-file matches — this shape is load-bearing because ctx-verify's `split_loc` parser depends on it. Any new lint script should follow both conventions.

Two scripts are placeholders for future dylint rules rather than real implementations: `cycle_check.sh` (checks `cargo modules dependencies` runs, doesn't detect cycles) and `rationale_check.py` (brace-heuristic size limits, not AST-based) — both documented in `docs/DYLINT_RULES.md`; don't mistake their passing exit code for the stronger guarantee their names imply.

The two `gen_*.sh` scripts are a different category — doc generators, not checks — but share a `--write`/`--check` mode pair and marker-based splicing (`<!-- BEGIN GENERATED ... -->` / `<!-- END GENERATED ... -->`) with the same divergent failure posture: `--write` exits immediately on hard error, `--check` accumulates `FAIL:` lines and keeps going. `gen_tool_contracts.sh` further couples to `target/debug` binaries and a hardcoded `DOCS` array that must stay in sync with which binaries implement `--contract`.

`machete_check.sh` and `no_allow_check.sh`/`retired_terms_check.sh` differ in failure posture: missing external tools (`cargo-machete`) are hard failures by design, not skips, since the check's entire job is the negative assertion.

intent_divergence: intent.md is absent, so no divergence can be assessed.